04632nam a22006615i 9780228015727DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280157277 a10.1515/97802280157272doi  a(DE-B1597)654738  a(OCoLC)1342441721  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHN801.Z9bS56 2023 7aPOL0530002bisacsh04a303.4096871/32231 aSinwell, Luke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Participation Paradox :bBetween Bottom-Up and Top-Down Development in South Africa /cLuke Sinwell. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b10 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in Protest, Power, and Resistance00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tParticipation's “Decapitation” -- tRecasting the Development “Saints” -- tThe People's Parliament and the Origins of Grassroots Democracy -- tElecting Working-Class Activists -- tBetween Bottom-Up and Top-Down Development -- tThe Struggle within the Struggle -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe last two decades have ushered in what has become known as a participatory revolution, with consultants, advisors, and non-profits called into communities, classrooms, and corporations alike to listen to ordinary people. With exclusively bureaucratic approaches no longer en vogue, authorities now opt for “open” forums for engagement. In The Participation Paradox Luke Sinwell argues that amplifying the voices of the poor and dispossessed is often a quick fix incapable of delivering concrete and lasting change. The ideology of public consultation and grassroots democracy can be a smokescreen for a cost-effective means by which to implement top-down decisions. As participation has become mainstreamed by governments around the world, so have its radical roots become tamed by neoliberal forces that reinforce existing relationships of power. Drawing from oral testimonies and ethnographic research, Sinwell presents a case study of one of the poorest and most defiant Black informal settlements in Johannesburg, South Africa – Thembelihle, which consists of more than twenty thousand residents – highlighting the promises and pitfalls of participatory approaches to development.Providing a critical lens for understanding grassroots democracy, The Participation Paradox foregrounds alternatives capable of reclaiming participation’s emancipatory potential.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity developmentzSouth AfricazThembelihlevCase studies. 0aDemocracyzSouth AfricazThembelihlevCase studies. 0aPolitical participationzSouth AfricazThembelihlevCase studies. 0aPoorzSouth AfricazThembelihlevCase studies. 0aSocial actionzSouth AfricazThembelihlevCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / African.2bisacsh  aAfrican studies.  aEmpowered Participatory Governance.  aSouth Africa.  adecolonial studies.  aparticipatory development.  apost-development.  asocial movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228015727?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228015727423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228015727/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles